snippet.textDisplay: The lesson kids: How to spot a sham - 1. Glitzy - shiny - to attract attention. I don't have much to sell, yet, so I need to dazzle you. Anyone can make promises even grand ones 2. Star-studded - the reason the scammer needs stars is to make up for not having all the other stuff, like technology, and engineering. 3. Money ! -" Come catch my money train!" - is what people who need your money say. An appeal to our need for more, "give me some and I'll give you a lot more back" sounds good. 4. Technology??? - When folks have extraordinary unsubstantiated, unverified technical claims, its time to investigate. If I say I invented antigravity you best check my research. 5. "We will be a _____ killer!" - this is not awful if the blank is something that has become a dinosaur in its industry, or is far behind where all think it should to be. When they say they're going to be better than the state of the art - red flag. That's really a form of name dropping, I want you to put me in the same category as them. 5. Track Record ? - What have they actually built? What else have they actually built. This is rocket science. Tesla by contrast built, sold, and supported an earlier car - the Roadster back in 2008. it wasn't some trick demo, it was a real car with real owners over years. Tesla didn't just fall out of the sky as a car maker, which Faraday did. So there, go back and watch the Faraday videos with these in mind, and I'll bet you spot the sham too.
